message.content:
To save text to a local file in a JavaScript web app, you can use the FileSaver.js library which provides a simple way to download or save files from the browser. Here's an example of how to do it:

1. First, include the FileSaver.js library in your HTML file by adding this script tag in the head section:
```html
<script src="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/FileSaver.js/2.0.5.0/FileSaver.min.js"></script>
```

2. Then, in your JavaScript code, create a function to save the text as a file:
```javascript
function saveAs(blob, fileName) {
  const blob = new Blob([text], {type: "text/plain;charset=utf-8"});
  const url = URL.createObjectURL(blob);
  const link = document.createElement('a');
  link.href = url;
  link.download = fileName;
  link.setAttribute("style", "display: none");
  document.body.appendChild(link);
  link.click();
  URL.revokeObjectURL(url);
}
```

3. Call the function with your text and desired file name:
```javascript
const text = "This is a sample text";
saveAs(new Blob([text], "sample-file.txt");
```
In this example, we create a new Blob object from the given text using the Blob constructor and pass it to the saveAs function along with the desired file name (in this case, "sample-file.txt"). The FileSaver.js library will handle the rest of the process for you, creating a temporary URL and downloading the file when the link is clicked.
